You should be using [Mockito][1] not [PowerMock][2]. PowerMock should be used to

&gt; enable mocking of static methods, constructors, final classes and methods, private methods, removal of static initializers and more

The examples that you provided do not imply the need for these features.

Using Mockito we can mock the `execute()` call like this: 

```java
@Test
public void testLogin() throws Exception {
    // Setup
    CloseableHttpClient httpClient = mock(CloseableHttpClient.class);
    CloseableHttpResponse response = mock(CloseableHttpResponse.class);
    when(httpClient.execute(any(HttpPost.class), any(HttpClientContext.class))).thenReturn(response);

    MainTest mainTest = new MainTest(httpClient);

    // Execute
    mainTest.login();

    // Assert
    ...
}

```
Note that the example assumes that the constructor of `MainTest` calls the superclass `Test` to instantiate the `CloseableHttpClient` and any other potential instance fields. 

  [1]: https://site.mockito.org/
  [2]: https://powermock.github.io/

